   Something wicked this way comes; Folklore Tapes continue their
  journey into the darkest alcoves of Britain's folkloric roots and
   bring us this compilation which journeys back to the origins of
Halloween and finds the Celtic festival Samhain. This release is just
 as unsettling as it is fascinating with supernatural themes seeping
 through the speakers on rectified cuts like 'Lullaby for Nosferatu'
  and 'Aos Si'. The holier sounds of Rob St John's Old Growth don't
come without a hint of the paranormal celebrations that this release
    focuses on. A searching compilation featuring Folklore Tapes
  mainstays such as Magpahi (Bird records), Ian Humberstone (Tisso
 Lake), Carl Turney & Brian Campbell (of the group Clinic) a few new
   names who could be shadowy producers connected to the Folkloric
  Pre-Cert world. With new members of the family in the form of Eva
Bowan and Mary Stark. Also of huge interest to many is the appearance
of a track from Children Of Alice, the group made up of James Cargill
  & Roj Stevens (previously of Broadcast) and Ghost Box affiliated
 artist Julian House. Coming complete with a pumpkin seed, the Time
    Team of the independent music world have successfully built a
            one-of-a-kind soundtrack for All Hallows Eve.
